entry.title: Eopsaltria australis
entry.content: On Tuesday night I got bored so I decided to record a video of some birds and see what I would get from that. So I used my iPod to record a short ish video and it came up with this! I'm so happy. There were about 7 types of bird species.

entry.title: Alisterus scapularis
entry.content: One of two King parrots that visited this morning. They liked the Olearias. Very comfortable with us, seemed very used to people.

entry.title: Alisterus scapularis
entry.content: Two King Parrots spent a lot of time round the house this morning. They seemed to be eating Olearia seeds. They seemed used to people.

entry.title: Dacelo novaeguineae
entry.content: Sitting on the window-sill watching its reflection. It let me get VERY close and stayed there for around 5 minutes then flew off. Very beautiful.

entry.title: Cacatua sanguinea/tenuirostris
entry.content: Thrilled to observe a corella sitting on the edge of his/her hole in the tree trunk.

entry.title: Calyptorhynchus funereus
entry.content: Yellow Tailed Black Cockatoo's around 20 of them, all cawing and a few were pulling bark off trees too (i'm guessing) find grubs that live inside the tree.

entry.title: Rhipidura albiscapa
entry.content: Enjoying what little water is around.

entry.title: Rhipidura rufifrons
entry.content: Taken with iPhone. Very flighty, very beautiful.

entry.title: Chenonetta jubata
entry.content: This was part of one family of two families on Whitakers Lane Riddells Creek. Seems to be a bumper year.

entry.title: Malurus cyaneus
entry.content: Left the window down slightly and this guy found his way and couldn't get out again.

entry.title: Petroica boodang
entry.content: Scarlet Robin in Conglomerate Gully, Riddells Creek. Location Approximate.

entry.title: Podargus strigoides
entry.content: Young Tawny Frogmouth in Conglomerate Gully, Riddells Creek.

entry.title: Cacatua galerita
entry.content: Cheeky. Eating garden-planted sunflower seeds in the township.

entry.title: Acanthorhynchus tenuirostris
entry.content: In a garden-planted Kangaroo Paw.

entry.title: Myiagra cyanoleuca
entry.content: I heard this bird move in at my place just over a year ago but this is the first time caught on camera.

entry.title: Acanthorhynchus tenuirostris
entry.content: In garden-planted Grevillea hybrid.

entry.title: Phylidonyris novaehollandiae
entry.content: In garden-planted Grevillea longistyla.

entry.title: Cincloramphus mathewsi
entry.content: New record for Riddells Creek. Very distinctive song.

entry.title: Cacomantis flabelliformis, Caligavis chrysops
entry.content: Heard both species calling. First of the season for me. A sign of pre-Spring.

entry.title: Platalea flavipes
entry.content: Juvenile, identified by greyish colored bill

entry.title: Egretta novaehollandiae
entry.content: Feathers seem to be very fluffed up for a cold day. May show breeding plumage?

entry.title: Circus assimilis
entry.content: Poor photo but a new species record for Riddells Creek. Seen briefly as it took off and flew behind trees on a grassland rail reserve. It was solitary and seemed very large. ID help from Chris Lindorff.

entry.title: Threskiornis molucca
entry.content: Lake Park.

entry.title: Daphoenositta chrysoptera pileata
entry.content: Male. 2nd pic shows typical upside-down foraging position while searching for insects. Group of about a dozen birds. This seems to be one of the most eastern records for Race pileata. See female in 9022.

entry.title: Daphoenositta chrysoptera pileata
entry.content: Female. Group of about a dozen birds. This seems to be one of the most eastern records for Race pileata. See also 9023.

entry.title: Acanthiza chrysorrhoa
entry.content: Mixed flock ~ 6 individuals feeding on ground with Willy Wagtail

entry.title: Corcorax melanorhamphos
entry.content: Family group of approx. 7 individuals. Differentiated from magpies and currawongs by (1) lack of visible white on the body when wings folded and (2) presence of large white patch outer half underside of wings.

entry.title: Turnix varius
entry.content: 3rd pic shows stationary, crouched position when caught in the open with Kookaburras calling as they flew over. Stayed motionless for about a minute.

entry.title: Strepera versicolor
entry.content: adult + young

entry.title: Dacelo novaeguineae
entry.content: Being watched closely by Grey Shrike-thrush.

entry.title: Coracina novaehollandiae, Platycercus eximius
entry.content: Poor photos (long way away) but Cuckoo-shrike is new for my property and Riddells Creek. Gill & I have been hearing a new call for a few days. Rosella has only been recorded once previously at my place too.

entry.title: Chalcites lucidus
entry.content: Flew into window. Placed in bush to recover by Barry Best.

entry.title: Aquila audax
entry.content: Saw it swoop down then up to gradually higher perches. Couldn't see ground but it was disturbed by two kangaroos 30s after swooping down. Perched for 5 minutes.

entry.title: Anthochaera carunculata
entry.content: Nice wattles. In garden-planted Gippsland Waratah (Telopea oreades).

entry.title: Podargus strigoides
entry.content: Male left, female right. They left the roosting spot at 6:18pm. These have been around for a few weeks, heard calling and/or observed on most days on a few roosting spots.

entry.title: 8 ids
entry.content: These 7 bird species were in & around this paddock tree over a 20 minute period. Also, 2 Indian Mynas flew off as I approached. The 3rd pic shows another bird I was unable to identify - short tail, chased off by New Hollands immediately on arrival.

entry.title: Podargus strigoides
entry.content: Pair spotted roosting on a dead Blackwood, among Eucalyptus aromaphloia. Second pic shows wing-marks on our window - the birds are feasting on Rain Moths (Hepialidae) on the windows at night at this time of year.

entry.title: Acanthorhynchus tenuirostris
entry.content: Feeding in a garden-planted Grevillea magnifica hybrid.

entry.title: Solanum laciniatum, Strepera graculina
entry.content: Ate 8-10 fruit. Initially seen perched in tree and thought it was a Grey Currawong (see pic 2). Pic 3 shows tail feather markings confirming it is the Pied Currawong. Probably moulting.

entry.title: Podargus strigoides
entry.content: Heard banging into windows after rain moths (Hepialidae).

entry.title: Phylidonyris novaehollandiae
entry.content: Washing in bird bath. White-naped Honeyeater flying off in background.

entry.title: Neochmia temporalis
entry.content: Adults and young

entry.title: Tachybaptus novaehollandiae
entry.content: There has been a resident pair on this pond for several years. However, very wary and difficult to photograph

entry.title: Aegotheles cristatus
entry.content: Recorded call.

entry.title: Turnix varius
entry.content: Single bird on side of road. Walked up to it and it walked into bush and started calling.

entry.title: Turnix varius
entry.content: Family on side of road.

entry.title: Ardea pacifica
entry.content: Observed on neighbours dam. Have not seen in this part of the world for years. Here due to wet season.

entry.title: Todiramphus sanctus
entry.content: Our annual visit from the Sacred King Fisher

entry.title: Ardea pacifica
entry.content: Spotted during a community walk by a large puddle.

entry.title: Acacia melanoxylon, Calyptorhynchus funereus
entry.content: Four in the Blackwood, Acacia melanoxylon eating seeds - spotted by Gill Best.

entry.title: Platycercus eximius
entry.content: Three birds. This is ony the second time I've seen this species at my place in 12 years. It is thick bush and dominated by Crimson Rosella.

entry.title: Callocephalon fimbriatum
entry.content: I saw 3 drinking from a puddle and they flew away but we found them again. Also we listened to them for a while.

entry.title: Lepidoptera spp., Ninox novaeseelandiae
entry.content: Southern Boobook feeding on moths at our lounge window after rain, which brought the moths.

entry.title: Strepera versicolor
entry.content: Heard distinctive call then spotted it.

entry.content: Species list for collection.

entry.title: Corvus mellori
entry.content: Sat there shouting at me.

entry.title: Podargus strigoides
entry.content: Flying back and forth towards the windows, chasing Rain Moths (Hepialidae).
